<H3> <TI>   Biographical Sketches of New Cabinet Members </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Biographical Sketches of New Cabinet Members </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Home Affairs Minister Hajime Ishii </H4>

<F P=102> OW2804085594 Tokyo KYODO in English 0745 GMT 28 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2804085594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 28 KYODO -- Newly appointed Home 
Affairs Minister Hajime Ishii played a major role in enacting 
political reform bills as the head of the House of 
Representatives Special Committee on Political Reform. Ishii, 
59, succeeded Kanju Sato of the Social Democratic Party (SDP) 
[of Japan -- SDPJ]. 
  A senior member of the coalition's core party Shinseito 
(Japan Renewal Party), Ishii served as director general of the 
National Land Agency under an administration of the Liberal 
Democratic Party (LDP). He joined Shinseito as new Prime 
Minister Tsutomu Hata and Ichiro Ozawa, the coalition's chief 
strategist, launched the party last year after bolting from the 
LDP, then the ruling party. 
  As an LDP legislator, Ishii held the posts of parliamentary 
vice labor minister and transport minister. 
  In 1977, he led a government mission to Dhaka, Bangladesh, 
where he negotiated with the hijackers of a Japan Airlines plane. 
  Currently, Ishii is chairman of a Friendship Association 
made 
up of parliamentarians of Japan and North Korea. 
  Ishii, who has studied in the United States, has a good 
working command of English. 
  Hailing from Hyogo Prefecture in western Japan, Ishii has 
been elected to the powerful House of Representatives eight 
times. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

