<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Biographical Sketches of New Cabinet Members </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Biographical Sketches of New Cabinet Members </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Agriculture, Forestry Minister Kato </H4>

<F P=102> OW2804090694 Tokyo KYODO in English 0801 GMT 28 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2804090694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 28 KYODO -- Newly appointed 
Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries Minister Mutsuki Kato, a 
veteran legislator of the House of Representatives, is known for 
his expertise on tax and financial policies. 
  Kato, 67, a member of Shinseito (Japan Renewal Party), 
replaced Eijiro Hata of the same party. He left the Liberal 
Democratic Party (LDP) last year to join the coalition's 
mainstream conservative and the LDP's breakaway party Shinseito, 
which was founded by Tsutomu Hata, new prime minister, and 
Ichiro Ozawa, the alliance's primary strategist. 
  Kato is known to be close to Ozawa. 
  In the LDP, Kato held such ministerial portfolios as Land 
Agency, Hokkaido Development Agency and agriculture. He formed 
his own group in 1991 after seceding from a major LDP faction 
led by Hiroshi Mitsuzuka, a veteran legislator who has held the 
posts of foreign, trade and transport ministers. 
  Kato also headed the LDP's Policy Affairs Council and 
Research Council on Tax System. 
  On political realignment, Kato shares a similar view with 
Ozawa, who is urging a two-party system, in which a unity party 
of coalition blocs rivals the LDP. 
  Kato, hailing from Okayama Prefecture, western Japan, has 
been elected to the powerful House of Representatives ten times. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

