<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Biographical Sketches of New Cabinet Members </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Biographical Sketches of New Cabinet Members </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    RMCA Director Koshiro Ishida </H4>

<F P=102> OW2804091494 Tokyo KYODO in English 0815 GMT 28 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2804091494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 28 KYODO -- Retained Management and 
Coordination Agency [RMCA] Director General Koshiro Ishida is 
expected to keep on tackling administrative reform centering on 
economic deregulation, which the United States has urged to 
reduce the huge imbalance in bilateral trade. 
  Ishida is the 63-year-old chairman of Komeito [Clean 
Government Party], the third-largest ruling coalition party, 
backed by the Buddhist group Soka Gakkai. His agency supervises 
state administration and takes charge of promoting economic 
deregulation. 
  Komeito's connection with Soka Gakkai was called into 
question at the Diet when the opposition Liberal Democratic 
Party quizzed Ishida over constitutional issues. The 
Constitution bans the state and its organs from conducting 
religious activities. 
  Ishida and Party Secretary General Yuichiro Ichikawa, the 
coalition's major strategist, have led Komeito for nearly five 
years. 
  Born in Hokkaido, Ishida started his Komeito career as an 
employee of Soka Gakkai's official newspaper after graduating 
from the Commerce Science Department of Meiji University. He 
comes from a family which has close relations with Soka Gakkai, 
one of the most successful religious movements in postwar Japan. 
  He was elected to the House of Representatives for the first 
time from the No. 6 constituency in Aichi Prefecture in 1967, 
the year Komeito first entered the lower house and voters have 
returned him nine more times. 
  He assumed the post of party chairman in 1989 following the 
resignation of former Chairman Junya Yano over his alleged 
involvement in the Recruit "stock-for-favors" scandal and other 
corruption cases involving the party's Diet members. The new 
chairman, however, met with setbacks both in the House of 
Councillors election in 1989 and the House of Representatives 
election in 1990, and was forced to change the party's direction 
and take a more centrist course. 
  In April 1990, Ishida made Komeito's position clear as a 
leading centrist party, distancing itself from reformist forces 
headed by the Social Democratic Party. By forming a union with 
another centrist force, the Democratic Socialist Party, Ishida 
cooperated skillfully with the then ruling Liberal Democratic 
Party in handling important issues in Diet debate. 
  In 1992, he played a key role in pushing a bill through the 
Diet that allows Japan to dispatch Self-Defense Forces personnel 
overseas to join in U.N. peacekeeping operations. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

