<H3> <TI>   Biographical Sketches of New Cabinet Members </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Biographical Sketches of New Cabinet Members </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Health Minister Keigo Ouchi </H4>

<F P=102> OW2804093294 Tokyo KYODO in English 0827 GMT 28 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2804093294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 25 KYODO -- Health and Welfare 
Minister Keigo Ouchi is expected to continue pushing for a 
thorough reform of the social security system to cope with 
Japan's aging society. 
  The 64-year-old chairman of the Democratic Socialist Party 
(DSP) shared former Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa's vision of 
a welfare society. However, he was strongly opposed to 
Hosokawa's surprise proposal in February to introduce a "7 
percent national welfare tax" on grounds the coalition parties 
were not consulted first. 
  The tax plan designed to partly finance tax cuts was 
scrapped 
the day after Hosokawa announced it. 
  Ouchi once called for a tie-up with Hosokawa's Japan New 
Party and new party Sakigake (Harbinger). He also said he 
favors a multiparty system but less than the current number, 
along with the coalition's leading Social Democratic Party (SDP) 
[of Japan -- SDPJ] and new party Sakigake, while Shinseito 
(Japan Renewal Party) and Komeito [Clean Government Party], the 
alliance's two core blocs, are urging coalition partners to 
consolidate into one party to fight the main opposition Liberal 
Democratic Party (LDP). 
  Ouchi, however, joined a new parliamentary group called 
"Kaishin" (Innovation), which was formed at his suggestion hours 
after Tsutomu Hata was elected new prime minister. The group 
comprises members of Shinseito, the Japan New Party of Hosokawa, 
the DSP, the newly established "Jiyuto" (Liberal Party) and 
Kaikaku-no-kai. 
  Together with other right-wing members who quit the former 
Socialist Party to found the DSP in 1960, Ouchi is known as a 
formulator of centrist policies. 
  In 1976, he was elected to the House of Representatives for 
the first time from a Tokyo constituency. After serving four 
consecutive terms in the lower house, he lost his seat in the 
1986 election, despite holding the DSP's No. 2 position of 
secretary general. 
  He recaptured his seat in the lower house and took office as 
chairman of the DSP. In last year's general election, he was 
elected for the sixth time. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

