<H3> <TI>   Biographical Sketches of New Cabinet Members </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Biographical Sketches of New Cabinet Members </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Development Agencies' Head Sato </H4>

<F P=102> OW2804121294 Tokyo KYODO in English 0924 GMT 28 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2804121294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 28 KYODO -- Moriyoshi Sato, who is to 
head the Hokkaido and Okinawa Development Agencies, is known to 
be a tenacious politician. Sato, 72, is a member of the 
coalition's core party Shinseito (Japan Renewal Party). 
  Sato made three abortive attempts to win a seat in the lower 
house before finally being elected to the House of 
Representatives. 
  He is currently serving his 9th term in the lower house. 
With the appointment Sato, a self-declared close aide of 
disgraced LDP [Liberal Democratic Party] kingpin Shin Kanemaru, 
returns to the political spotlight. 
  It was Sato who in August 1992 read out Kanemaru's statement 
announcing his resignation from the LDP vice presidency over his 
acceptance of 500 million yen in undeclared donations from a 
scandal-ridden trucking firm. 
  Sato, who hails from Hiroshima, is said to have adapted 
quickly to the post-Kanemaru era, distancing himself from the 
fallen LDP powerbroker. 
  While serving as agriculture minister, Sato managed to break 
the deadlock in fishery rights negotiations with the former 
Soviet Union in 1985. In his LDP days, he gained experience 
mainly in the fields of transport and telecommunications. 
  He has also served as National Land Agency director general. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

