<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kono on Confronting New Government Over Budget </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kono on Confronting New Government Over Budget </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2804110194 Tokyo KYODO in English 0955 GMT 28 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2804110194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 28 KYODO -- Opposition Liberal 
Democratic Party (LDP) President Yohei Kono on Thursday [28 
April] expressed willingness to confront the newly inaugurated 
administration of Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata through 
parliamentary debate on the fiscal 1994 budget. 
  The LDP "will take issue of (some aspects of the budget bill 
the LDP cannot accept) and urge the government to amend what 
should be amended," the leader of Japan's largest opposition 
party told a group of reporters. 
  Japan's fiscal 1994 state budget to cover outlays for the 
12-month period that started on April 1 is already one month 
overdue. 
  Kono also criticized Shinseito [Japan Renewal Party], a key 
coalition party, of trying to dominate the policy-making 
process. "We cannot deny the fact that Shinsieto has come to 
assume greater weight in the government," he said. "Without 
question, it will be a fragile cabinet, as the ruling coalition 
has been reduced to a parliamentary minority." 
  He rapped Shinseito, a former LDP breakaway, for maintaining 
the "two-tiered power structure," in an apparent reference to 
the growing dominance by Shinseito Secretary General Ichiro 
Ozawa of the policy-making process. Hata "is not the prime 
power in Shinseito," he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

