<H3> <TI>   ROK, Japanese Defense Chiefs Agree to Exchanges </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    ROK, Japanese Defense Chiefs Agree to Exchanges </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK2604113094 Seoul YONHAP in English 1110 GMT 26 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2604113094 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 26 (YONHAP) -- South Korea and Japan on 
Tuesday agreed to exchange naval vessels' goodwill visits and to 
mutually inform about their war planes' flights through 
overlapping defense identification zones near Kushu and Tsushima. 
  The agreement was made during talks between visiting Korean 
Defense Minister Yi Pyong-tae and Japanese Defense Agency 
Minister Kazuo Aichi. 
  Under the agreement, a South Korean cruiser is expected to 
visit Japan this fall, followed by a similar visit to Korea by 
Japanese Maritime Defense Agency vessels. 
  The two ministers decided to expand military personnel 
exchanges and take others steps to further promote mutual 
understanding through substantial military exchanges, the report 
said. 
  Exchanging opinions on other matters of common interest, Yi 
and Aichi agreed that the North Korean nuclear question should 
be resolved forthwith and North Korea should promptly return to 
the Nuclear Nonproliferation Treaty if only to fulfill its 
obligations as a member of the world community. 
  The Yi-Aichi talks lasted one and a half hours beginning 
4:15 
PM. 
  Yi is set to tour major Self-Defense Force installations and 
pay a call on Prime Minister-designate Tsutomu Hata before 
leaving Japan for the next leg of his tour, Moscow, on Thursday. 

</TEXT>

