<F P=100> SOUTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Cambodia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage on Khmer Rouge Activities Continues </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reportage on Khmer Rouge Activities Continues </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Son Sen Called `New Power' </H4>

<F P=102> BK2604134694 Phnom Penh AKP in English 1010 GMT 26 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> BK2604134694 </F>
<F P=104>  Phnom Penh AKP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Phnom Penh AKP April 26 -- Son Sen, a member of the 
Democratic Kampuchea (Khmer Rouge) is now reportedly the new 
power in the Khmer Rouge, said CAMBODIA TIMES, an 
English-language local newspaper, in its recent issue. 
  Contrary to common belief and reports, Son Sen, who was 
relieved of his duties in May 1992 after losing a high-level 
dispute over whether the Khmer Rouge should pull out of the 
UN-organized peace plan, is very much in control within the 
Khmer Rouge. 
  According to senior government intelligence sources, Son Sen 
is in control of the Khmer Rouge rank and file and its political 
platform. 
  He is also said to be directing the military effort against 
the currently victorious Royal Cambodian Armed Forces (RCAF). 
  The source said that Son Sen is now directing the 
counter-attacks against the RCAF forces at Pailin from a 
stronghold at Phum Malai mountains, one of the last remaining 
Khmer Rouge military bastions. 
  He is also reportedly responsible for the Khmer Rouge's 
successful counter-attack at Anlung Veng. 
  They said that the fact that Khmer Rouge leaders like Pol 
Pot 
and Khieu Samphan and commanders like Ta Mok were reportedly no 
longer in the country but have sought sanctuary in a 
neighbouring country, has fuelled claims that the Khmer Rouge 
leadership is now in quiet disarray with the military losses, 
especially that of Pailin. 
  Meanwhile, Pailin has reportedly come under heavy shelling 
in 
recent days and the Khmer Rouge were said to be operating in 
groups of not more than eight members who were involved in 
hit-and-run tactics as well as harassment of RCAF personnel and 
commanders. 
  Military sources said that the capture of Phnum Malai from 
the Khmer Rouge was the best way of ensuring peace, Pailin and 
Battambang as it will relieve Khmer Rouge pressure from these 
two areas. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

