<F P=102>   BK2704091694 Quezon City PTV-4 Television Network in English 
0653 GMT 27 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK2704091694 </F>
<F P=104>  Quezon City PTV-4 Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Weekly news conference by President Fidel V. Ramos with </F>
domestic and foreign correspondents at Malacanang Palace in 
Manila -- live] 
  [Excerpt] [passage omitted] [Ramos] As agreed at the 
Cabinet meeting yesterday, I am sending Vice President Joseph 
Estrada as my special representative to the inauguration of the 
new South African state, whose president will be proclaimed or 
inaugurated in Pretoria on 10 May 1994. This was upon the 
invitation of the Government of South Africa. 
  As most of you already know, especially the old timers, the 
Philippines has had a long and distinguished record in being at 
the forefront of the anti-apartheid crusade. As one of the 
founding fathers of the UN special committee against apartheid, 
the Philippines prominently and consistently took the lead in 
the cause for equality for all South Africans. 
  Among the members of the vice president's delegation are 
Ambassador Taday, who is our ambassador and envoy extra ordinary 
and plenipotentiary to South Africa; Mrs. Estrada; the chief of 
staff of the vice president, Buddy Abentajado; Mrs. Abentajado; 
and a senior officer from the Department of Foreign Affairs, Mr. 
Miguel Bautista. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

