<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Presidential Control of NSP Said Constitutional </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Presidential Control of NSP Said Constitutional </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK2804081294 Seoul YONHAP in English 0748 GMT 28 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2804081294 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, April 28 (YONHAP) -- The Constitutional Court 
ruled Thursday that the Government Organization Law, which 
places the Agency for National Security Planning (NSP) under the 
direct control of the president, is allowed under the 
Constitution. 
  A panel of all the Constitutional Court judges, headed by 
Judge Hwang To-yon, handed down the ruling in an appeal filed by 
Rep. Pak Chan-chong of the new Political Reform Party and others. 
  Pak and his colleagues argued that the Government 
Organization Law violates the Constitution by putting the 
intelligence agency under the president, not the prime minister. 
  "The NSP could not be included in administrative ministries 
and offices' as specified in the 86th provision of the 
Constitution," the ruling said. 
  "It is a matter of course, therefore, that the NSP could not 
come under the control of the prime minister," it added. 
  Rep. Pak and 56 lawyers including practicing attorney Chang 
Ki-uk filed the appeal in May 1989 when Song Chong-tae, an aide 
to Rep. Yi Chol, was arrested by the NSP on charges of violating 
the Military Secret Protection Law. 
  They claimed that the NSP, which the government had no 
constitutional ground to establish, violated the Constitution 
when it arrested Song. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-7255 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas082_d_94017" </HT>


