<F P=101> Australia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Evans Supports More NATO Air Strikes in Bosnia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Evans Supports More NATO Air Strikes in Bosnia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK2104022494 Melbourne Radio Australia in English 0100 GMT 
21 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK2104022494 </F>
<F P=104>  Melbourne Radio Australia </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Australia's foreign minister, Gareth Evans, says 
the threat of more air strikes by NATO to protect United Nations 
safe areas in Bosnia-Herzegovina provides some ground for 
optimism. Senator Evans said he supports the decision and hopes 
the show of force will bring all parties back to the negotiating 
table. However, he warns that the threat of bombing alone may 
not be enough to stop the violence in Bosnia. 
  [Begin Evans recording] Well, it is not clear that there is 
any other alternative at the moment. I mean the downside risks 
are that the bombing won't be enough without ground support of 
the kind that there is still no will to supply. The risk is 
also that this kind of action in these new exclusionary zones 
will simply generate additional complications elsewhere. [End 
recording] 
  Meanwhile, Senator Evans has welcomed the Zulu Inkatha 
Party's decision to participte in the South African elections, 
saying it should reduce the level of violence in the country. 
  Senator Evans said although sporadic violence can still be 
expected in South Africa in the lead-up to the election, the 
across-the-board bloodbath which was feared can hopefully be 
avoided. 

</TEXT>

