<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Plane Crash `Temporarily' Resuscitates Cabinet </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Plane Crash `Temporarily' Resuscitates Cabinet </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2604162694 Tokyo KYODO in English 1615 GMT 26 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2604162694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 27 KYODO -- The Hosokawa cabinet, 
which resigned en masse on Monday [25 April], was temporarily 
resuscitated Tuesday night to deal with issues surrounding the 
crash of a China Airlines jetliner at Nagoya Airport in which 
some 220 people died. 
  Setting aside the differences that have brought Japan's 
political machine in Tokyo to a virtual standstill, former Prime 
Minister Morihiro Hosokawa and his ex-cabinet ministers of 
different political stripes were busy contacting each other to 
keep abreast of developments in the air disaster. 
  At a hastily arranged emergency cabinet session, Transport 
Minister Shigeru Ito, of the Social Democratic Party [of Japan, 
SDPJ] (SDP), was appointed head of a special task force to 
oversee the government's handling of the plane crash, government 
officials said. 
  Ito and Home Affairs Minister Kanju Sato, also of the SDP, 
will arrive in Nagoya Airport early Wednesday by helicopter. 
  The SDP said early Tuesday it was quitting the post-Hosokawa 
coalition government of Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata due to the 
sudden formation by five parties of an intraparliamentary group 
of which it was not informed. 
  Masayoshi Takemura, chief cabinet secretary under the 
Hosokawa cabinet, was also involved in the China Airlines plane 
case, telling reporters, "politics is in an unusual stage, but 
we want to deal with (the issue) without delay." 
  Under the Japanese Constitution, the departing cabinet has 
the responsibility to handle major day-to-day operations until 
the incoming administration is fully in place. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

