<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Japan's Fujii Addresses G-7 Finance Ministers </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Japan's Fujii Addresses G-7 Finance Ministers </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2504000994 Tokyo KYODO in English 0001 GMT 25 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2504000994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Washington, April 24 KYODO -- Japan will enact 
lasting income tax cuts by year's end, Finance Minister Hirohisa 
Fujii told his counterparts from seven major industrial nations 
Sunday. 
  The demand for Tokyo to extend this year's 6 trillion yen in 
income and residential tax cuts, to spur domestic demand and 
reduce its trade surplus, came again at Sunday's meeting in 
Washington of the Group of Seven (G-7) finance ministers and 
central bank chiefs. 
  Fujii told a news conference that he responded by saying 
multi year tax cuts will be enacted this year, as promised by 
the coalition government of outgoing Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokawa. 
  Japanese officials have said Fujii carried a message that a 
new government to be launched Monday will carry on Hosokawa's 
reforms. Foreign Minister Tsutomu Hata is certain to succeed 
Hosokawa as premier. 
  Fujii said the finance leaders of Britain, Canada, France, 
Germany, Italy and the United States also confirmed with him 
"the shared understanding that excessive changes in exchange 
rates are undesirable." 
  He said he stressed to the meeting "that exchange rates 
should reflect economic fundamentals and that excessive changes 
are undesirable, and all the countries confirmed this." He said 
they agreed on "close cooperation" on the exchange market. 
  Foreign exchange volatility is also undesirable for stock 
and 
bond markets, Fujii said. 
  Bank of Japan Governor Yasushi Mieno told the same news 
conference that he recognizes U.S. economic recovery as genuine 
and that other countries are steadily moving in a brighter 
economic direction. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

