<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Discusses Unstable Currency Rates </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Discusses Unstable Currency Rates </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2504004994 Tokyo KYODO in English 0037 GMT 25 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2504004994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Kohei Murayama] </F>
  [Text] Washington, April 24 KYODO -- A reaffirmed accord 
by the Group of Seven (G-7) industrialized nations on 
stabilizing exchange rates reflects Japan's concern over the 
adverse economic effects of currency volatility, Japanese 
Finance Minister Hirohisa Fujii said Sunday. 
  "I expressed my view that unstable rates will have 
undesirable effects on the stock and bond markets and cool off 
business sentiment to put a damper on the economy," Fujii told a 
press conference after a meeting of G-7 finance ministers and 
central bankers. 
  Fujii said the G-7 financial leaders reconfirmed their past 
accord to closely cooperate to realize stable currency rates 
reflecting economic fundamentals. "The stronger growth nations 
were referred to as the United States, Canada, and Britain, and 
the weaker nations as Japan and other G-7 nations." Fujii said. 
  Fujii said he described the state of Japan's economy as 
"still generally sluggish," but stressed that the February 15.25 
trillion yen economic package will help Japan attain a 
full-fledged recovery. 
  Fujii also said that he explained that the Japanese ruling 
coalition parties agreed to implement multi-year income tax cuts 
in a policy accord agreed last Friday on forming a new cabinet. 
  On the current account surplus, Fujii said, "the trend has 
clearly reversed," citing the change in the effects of external 
demand on Japan's economic growth. 
  External demand pushed down Japan's real gross domestic 
product (GDP) by 0.3 percentage point, while domestic demand 
boosted it by 0.4 point to attain a 0.1 percent growth in fiscal 
1993 that ended March 31, Fujii said. 

</TEXT>

