<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-083-A </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  27 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Banks Selling Credits Rights on Former USSR </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Banks Selling Credits Rights on Former USSR </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2904042594 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 27 Apr 
94 Morning Edition p 7--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2904042594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Japanese banks are actively selling their credit 
rights on the former USSR because repayment by Russia, which 
took over the former USSR's obligations, remains uncertain. 
Total Japanese bank loans to the former Soviet Union totaled 
200 billion yen at the end of March, nearly 100 billion yen less 
than in September 1993. These credits are being sold to 
European investors through European commercial banks and 
securities firms. In some cases, East European countries with 
outstanding loans with Russia are buying them to offset such 
credits. 
  A total of five or six city banks, including Fuji Bank and 
Daiichi Kangyo Bank, and a number of local banks are reportedly 
selling off their credit rights with the former USSR. 
  Most of Japanese banks-held credit rights with the former 
USSR are loans to the Russian Bank for Foreign Economic 
Relations [BFER]. The current price of credit rights on the 
Russian BFER being dealt on the international financial market 
is 27-28 percent of the face value. It has been falling since 
last December, when the price saw its peak at 54 percent. 
Although the main cause of a drop in prices is a rise in 
long-term interest rates, some analysts point out: "Japanese 
banks' active sales are another cause of a drop in the prices." 
  In addition to those of former the USSR, Japanese banks are 
actively disposing of bad loans of other nations. Last year, 
they disposed of their claimable assets of Argentina by changing 
them to Argentine government-issued bonds (Brady bonds). They 
also disposed of their credit rights with Brazil last April. 
For Japanese banks, how to sell off credits with the former 
Soviet Union is another major issue. And with this in mind, 
they have started selling their credit rights with the former 
Soviet Union. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-7286 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas083__a94011" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-083-A </AU>
