<F P=100> Thailand </F>
<H3> <TI>   Poor Security Measures in South Hurt Investment </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Poor Security Measures in South Hurt Investment </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK2804024694 Bangkok THE NATION in English 28 Apr 94 p A7 </F>
<F P=103> BK2804024694 </F>
<F P=104>  Bangkok THE NATION </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Prime Minister Chuan Likphai yesterday admitted that 
security measures in the South are inadequate. 
  He said violence in the region including last year's 
torching 
of more than 30 schools in the southernmost provinces and 
Saturday's bomb blast at Nakhon Si Thammarat's railway station, 
had adversely affected investment in the South. 
  Chuan told a gathering of Islamic religious leaders that 
while people in the South may have become accustomed to such 
incidents, those outside the region were scared by the press 
reports. 
  He said religious leaders could help solve the problem of 
violence by giving officials information when incidents occurred 
and telling people in their communities to behave themselves. 
  Many acts of sabotage have occurred in the South since Chuan 
took office in 1992, the bomb last Saturday which killed three 
people and injured at least 27 others being only the most recent. 
  The opposition has threatened to file a no-confidence motion 
against the government over public security. 
  Deputy Interior Minister Suthat Ngoenmun said it was the 
duty 
and right of the opposition to file a no-confidence motion. The 
government must publicly explain to avoid confusion, he said. 
  He said police should come up with better measures and 
intelligence to prevent violence. Police performance in dealing 
with bombing incidents dissatisfied the people, the press and 
the opposition, Suthat said. 
  "I'm not happy. I'm not satisfied with police performance in 
preventing and suppressing crime," Suthat said. "Intelligence 
services should be better. I don't know what their problem is, 
since the government has allocated a budget for them." 
  He said police chief Prathin Santipraphop should not comment 
on cases while things are still unclear. This only confuses the 
public and allows the culprits to escape. 
  Suthat said evidence, witnesses and investigative procedures 
should be kept secret. Police should not publicly reveal 
everything because this affects the investigations. 
  He said Pol Gen [Police General] Prathin is a capable 
officer, but he may not have a strong enough team to help him. 
  Deputy Interior Minister Chamni Sakdiset said Interior 
Minister Chawalit Yongchaiyut was ready to face the opposition 
in Parliament, should it initiate a censure debate. 
  He said police should investigate all possible motives 
behind 
Saturday's bomb blast, including personal affairs and politics. 

</TEXT>

