<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S., Japanese Develop Low-Voltage CMOS Chip </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    U.S., Japanese Develop Low-Voltage CMOS Chip </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2504060094 Tokyo KYODO in English 0537 GMT 25 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2504060094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 25 KYODO -- Japan's Toshiba Corp. and 
the U.S.-owned National Semiconductor Japan Ltd. and Nippon 
Motorola Ltd. announced Monday they will start sample shipments 
in late may of a family of low-voltage semiconductor they have 
jointly developed. 
  The companies said the pure three-volt CMOS (complementary 
metal oxide semiconductor) logic family with five-volt tolerant 
inputs and outputs is the first of its kind in the world. 
  The devices operate at pure three volts or at both three and 
five volts in the same design without sacrificing performance, 
the companies said. 
  They said the devices are designed for use in notebook 
personal computers, portable personal information tools and 
other portable devices. 

</TEXT>

