<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   EPA Official: IMF `Underestimated' Outlook </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    EPA Official: IMF `Underestimated' Outlook </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2204100394 Tokyo KYODO in English 0949 GMT 22 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2204100394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 22 KYODO -- The International Monetary 
Fund (IMF) underestimated the Japanese economy in its recent 
economic outlook, a senior Economic Planning Agency (EPA) 
official said Friday [22 April]. 
  Tsutomu Tanaka, the EPA's vice minister, said the IMF did 
not 
sufficiently take into account the effects of Japan's economic 
stimulus package and signs of recovery seen lately in 
consumption. 
  "It is difficult to understand why the IMF revised down its 
projection for Japanese economy from the previous outlook issued 
lastfall," Tanaka said. 
  The IMF issued an outlook for world economy earlier this 
week, saying Japan's economy is expected to stay sluggish in 
1994, with the annual growth rate remaining weak at 0.7 percent, 
revised down from a 2.0 percent growth forecast by itself last 
September. 
  Asked about a drop in the nation's February household 
spending, Tanaka admitted that the recovery is not yet strong. 
  "Because the recovery momentum is still weak, it is easily 
affected by such things as unfavorable weather," he said. 
  On Thursday, the government announced the February household 
spending dropped by 0.5 percent from a year earlier, ending a 
four- month streak of rise on year. It attributed the drop 
partly to snowfalls that prevented consumers from shopping. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

