<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Urges Greater Job Training Role </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Urges Greater Job Training Role </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2204025894 Tokyo KYODO in English 0228 GMT 22 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2204025894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 22 KYODO -- Labor Minister Chikara 
Sakaguchi said Friday [22 April] local and central governments 
should take a greater role in job training. 
  Job training is focus of a new medium- and long-term program 
to be announced in May, he told reporters. 
  Up to now job training has been provided mainly by 
corporations. Both the central and local governments should 
review ways to take on some of the role in training workers 
along with the private sector, he said. 
  He pointed to the need to study how to deal with job 
training 
at small and medium-sized companies, which account for roughly 
90 percent of all companies in Japan. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

