<F P=100> Mongolia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Demonstration Termed `Major' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Demonstration Termed `Major' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2404132394 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1148 
GMT 24 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2404132394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Ulaanbaatar, 24 Apr (ITAR-TASS) -- The center of the 
Mongolian capital today witnessed a major antigovernment 
demonstration for the second day running. According to various 
sources, between 3,000 and 5,000 citizens took part in it. The 
demonstrators, chanting slogans demanding the resignation of the 
Cabinet of Prime Minister [Puntsaqiyn] Jasray, have blocked the 
entrances to the building where the government is sitting. In 
view of the peaceful nature of the demonstration, the security 
forces units that came to the square have not interfered. 
  The latest demonstration in central Ulaanbaatar has become 
yet another move in the campaign of pressure exerted by the 
opposition on the government which its opponents call "corrupt." 
Active protests began two weeks ago when several dozens of 
mainly young Mongols went on a hunger strike, not expecting, 
according to them, to achieve their aim -- to make the 
government surrender -- by other means. However, while the 
conflict developed those on a hunger strike inclined toward a 
compromise, trying to achieve not the resignation of, but only a 
meeting with, the prime minister. They also want to receive 
from the government a document promising to carry out effective 
socioeconomic reforms. Among the demands is the need for 
decisive measures in the fight against crime and inadmissibility 
of the further impoverishment of the population. 
  According to Jasray, head of the Mongolian Government, he 
has 
no reason to resign. Meanwhile, an official investigation has 
been started into the accusations of corruption made by the 
opposition. Mongolian legislators appeared alongside government 
officials in them. Competent bodies promise to finish the 
investigation within two weeks. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

