<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Daily Criticizes South for Barring Mun Mourners </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Daily Criticizes South for Barring Mun Mourners </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK2804051094 Pyongyang KCNA in English 0445 GMT 28 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2804051094 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Rude and Inhumane Barbarous Act" -- KCNA headline] </F>
  [Text] Pyongyang, April 28 (KCNA) -- NODONG SINMUN today 
carries a commentary hitting out at the South Korean authorities 
for blocking the southern trip of a delegation of the North side 
which had been invited to a memorial service on the one 
hundredth day after the death of the Rev. Mun Ik-hwan. 
  Recalling that the Rev. Mun was a pioneer of the 
reunification movement who fought till the last moments of his 
life for the reunification of the country, the common cause of 
the nation, and a highly reputed patriotic champion of 
reunification widely known to the compatriots at home and 
abroad, the analyst says: 
  The South Korean rulers had barred a mourners' group of the 
North side from going to Seoul to express condolences at the 
bier of the Rev. Mun in January and this time blocked the 
southern trip of a delegation of the North side which was to 
attend a memorial service on the one hundredth day since his 
death. This is a very immoral and rude act. 
  The national funeral committee for the late Rev. Mun Ik-hwan 
decided to hold the memorial service on the one hundredth day of 
his death as a national function and invited compatriots in the 
North and overseas. And the North side decided to send a 
delegation out of the noble sense of obligation for the deceased 
and his bereaved family and ardent desire for national unity. 
  Expressing condolences and honoring the memory of the 
deceased is rather a humanitarian matter than a political matter. 
  Such anti-human group of traitors as the Kim Yong-sam group 
which seeks confrontation and war in league with outside forces 
while lowering a checkbar on the Southern trip of fellow 
countrymen for mourning the deceased, must be removed from the 
nation. 

</TEXT>

