<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Groups Back Repatriation of POW's </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Groups Back Repatriation of POW's </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK2704231794 Pyongyang KCNA in English 1505 GMT 27 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2704231794 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Pyongyang, April 27 (KCNA) -- Burundian and 
Mozambican organizations strongly urged the repatriation of old 
Kim In-so and Ham Se-hwan, unconverted long-term prisoners in 
South Korea, to the northern half of Korea and the release of An 
Hak-sop, an old man. 
  Kim In-so and Ham Se-hwan who were soldiers of the Korean 
People's Army during the Korean war served more than 30 years in 
prison, after taken prisoners, for the mere reason that they 
refused to recant their belief. And An Hak-sop is now serving 
in prison for more than 40 years since he was arrested, charged 
with being "a spy of North Korea". 
  The Burundi-Korea Friendship Association and the Burundian 
Group for the Study of the Chuche Idea in a joint protest letter 
to the South Korean authorities April 19 said the repatriation 
of Kim In-so and Ham Se-hwan and the release of An Hak-sop 
accord with the humanitarian spirit and the UN principles on 
human rights and democracy. 
  The Mozambican committee for friendship with the people of 
the Democratic People's Republic of Korea in a statement April 
13 said Kim In-so and Ham Se-hwan were living a life worse than 
death in South Korea without any protection, though they are 
sick. It strongly urged an immediate return of the old men who 
want to meet with their dear relatives and friends at home even 
at this late hour of their life. The South Korean authorities 
must know clearly that if they refused to return the old men, 
they would face curses and a stern judgement by the Korean 
people and the world people, warned the statement. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

