Daily Report 
<DATE1>  25 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   IAEA on `Essential Inspection' of DPRK </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    IAEA on `Essential Inspection' of DPRK </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK2504115494 Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network in Korean 1100 GMT 25 
Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> SK2504115494 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Korean </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The International Atomic Energy Agency [IAEA] 
initially planned to dispatch a two-person inspection team to 
North Korea early this week in connection with the replacement 
of nuclear fuel rods. However, North Korea has not allowed 
essential inspection activities. Thus, the IAEA decided to 
temporarily withhold dispatching the inspection team. 
  David Kyd, director of IAEA Information Department, said 
that 
the IAEA, when accepting the North Korean proposal concerning 
the replacement of nuclear fuel rods, demanded that North Korea 
allow essential inspection activities, and requested the 
issuance of visas for two inspectors to be dispatched as advance 
team members. 
  Director Kyd said that the IAEA urged North Korea to allow 
essential inspection activities pertaining to the replacement 
of nuclear fuel rods. He stressed that as long as North Korea 
does not show a change in its basic position, the dispatch of 
the inspection team will be withheld. 
  Director Kyd said, however, that if North Korea flexibly 
accepts the IAEA proposal by Thursday [28 April], the IAEA would 
consider dispatching an inspection team on Thursday. 

</TEXT>

