<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   DPRK Envoy on Allowing IAEA Inspections </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    DPRK Envoy on Allowing IAEA Inspections </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK2904024694 Seoul YONHAP in English 0241 GMT 29 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2904024694 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] United Nations, April 28 (YONHAP) -- Pyongyang is 
ready to allow additional inspections by the International 
Atomic Energy Agency [IAEA] considering the latest change in the 
situation on an inter-Korean exchange of special envoys after 
examining the future attitudes of the United States and the 
IAEA, North Korean Ambassador to the United Nations Pak Kil-yon 
said in a press conference here Thursday [28 April]. 
  Pak seemed to be attaching a condition to the offer but his 
remark attracted attention since permitting further checks of 
its nuclear facilities would be considered a breakthrough in the 
lengthy impasse related to the North Korean nuclear issue. 
  South Korea recently withdrew the inter-Korean exchange of 
special envoys as a condition for a third round of high-level 
U.S.- North Korea talks. 
  North Korea previously maintained that any further 
inspections should be discussed at a third round of high-level 
talks with the United States. 
  Pak reiterated Pyongyang's position that the 1953 Armistice 
Agreement should be replaced by a peace accord between North 
Korea and the United States. 

</TEXT>

