<H3> <TI>   IAEA Proposes Fuel Rod Change Observation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    IAEA Proposes Fuel Rod Change Observation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK2904004794 Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network in Korean 2200 GMT 28 
Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> SK2904004794 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Korean </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By correspondent Cha Man-sun from Vienna] </F>
  [Text] The International Atomic Energy Agency [IAEA] has 
sent a telegram to North Korea and urged North Korea to allow 
inspection when it replaces nuclear fuel rods under the 
condition that the IAEA conducts sample-taking and surveys gamma 
rays later. The IAEA proposed that it will send a five-member 
team to North Korea early next week. 
  IAEA spokesman David Kyd said that although the IAEA sent 
this message to the North Korean side, there is no change in the 
IAEA's basic position to conduct essential inspection activities 
pertaining to the replacement of the nuclear fuel rods. 
  It appears that the IAEA, changing its previous policy, 
intends to conduct inspections in a flexible manner because it 
expects that there will be a change in the North Korean position 
according to the results of U.S.-North Korea contacts to be held 
in the future. 

</TEXT>

