<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-083 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  28 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S.-DPRK Working-Level Contact Reported </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    U.S.-DPRK Working-Level Contact Reported </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK2904001194 Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network in Korean 2200 GMT 28 
Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> SK2904001194 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Korean </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [YONHAP report from New York] </F>
  [Text] The United States and North Korea held a 
working-level contact in New York early this morning and 
intensively discussed the presence of an International Atomic 
Energy Agency [IAEA] inspection team when North Korea replaces 
nuclear fuel rods, the additional inspection of a radiochemical 
experimental power station in Yongbyon, and the creation of 
conditions for holding a third round of U.S.-North Korean 
high-level talks. 
  Kim Chong-so, deputy ambassador at the North Korean mission 
to the United Nations, said that a contact with the U.S. side 
will be held today, and confirmed that dialogue between the 
United States and North Korea has been resumed. 
  Today's working contact is to be held after two months since 
the last U.S.-North Korean contact was held on 25 February, when 
the two sides agreed on the principle of inspecting declared 
nuclear facilities in North Korea. 
  Tom Hubbard, deputy U.S. assistant secretary of state, and 
other officials attended the contact for the U.S. side, and Kim 
Chong-so, deputy ambassador, and Han Song-yol, political 
councilor, represented the North Korean side. 
  At the contact, the U.S. side urged North Korea to allow an 
additional inspection of the radiochemical experimental power 
station and to create conditions for a third round of talks, 
stressing that the ROK side already withdrew the demand for the 
exchange of North-South special envoys--a condition for the 
third round of U.S.-North Korea high-level talks--and showed 
flexibility. 
  The United States also pointed out that North Korean nuclear 
activities should be frozen while the U.S.-North Korean dialogue 
is ongoing, and asked the North Korean side not to load 
[changchak] fuel rods again in the five-megawatt nuclear reactor 
in Yongbyon. The United States requested that the presence and 
inspection activities of the IAEA inspection team be 
sufficiently guaranteed. 
  The North Korean side, however, claimed that it kept all of 
the promises it made previously, including allowing all 
inspections to ensure continuity of safeguards of nuclear 
facilities. Thus, North Korea showed the position of resolving 
the issue of additional inspections, the issue of supporting the 
work of turning North Korean nuclear facilities into light-water 
reactors, and the issue of improving U.S.-North Korean 
relations, in a package, by convening the third round of 
U.S.-North Korean high-level talks at an early date. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

