<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Supreme Court Rejects Appeal by U.S. Soldier </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Supreme Court Rejects Appeal by U.S. Soldier </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK2904093194 Seoul YONHAP in English 0925 GMT 29 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2904093194 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, April 19 (YONHAP) -- The Supreme Court 
rejected Friday an appeal by a 22-year-old American soldier 
charged with murdering a Korean bar girl, confirming the 
original sentence of 15 years in prison. The high court found 
Pvt. Kenneth Markle guilty of intentional murder and dismissed 
his plea of self-defense in view of the circumstances 
surrounding the murder. 
  As soon as it receives the ruling, the Justice Ministry will 
ask the delivery of the convict from the U.S. Forces Korea in 
accordance with the Korea-U.S. Status of Forces Agreement (SOFA) 
to put him in a juvenile prison in Chonan. Currently three 
American soldiers are confined in Chonan prison. 
  The U.S. side can reject Korean Government requests to claim 
soldiers, civilian employees in the military or their dependents 
accused of a criminal offense on the ground of "sympathetic 
consideration" provision of the SOFA but must comply with the 
requests when they are found guilty in a court of law. 
  The Korean prosecution originally sought to put Markle under 
its custody in view of the cruelty and inhumanness of his murder 
of Yun Kum-i in October 1992, but it had to indict him without 
physical detention since the American forces refused to turn him 
over in accordance with the provision. He is currently detained 
at a U.S. base here. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

