<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Creditors Give Iran Moratorium on Debts </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Creditors Give Iran Moratorium on Debts </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK2904120194 Seoul YONHAP in English 1154 GMT 29 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2904120194 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, April 29 (YONHAP) -- Another moratorium has 
been granted to the outstanding debts Iran owes to South Korean 
traders. 
  A business source said on Friday that a visiting Iranian 
Central Bank delegation and representatives of South Korean 
creditors agreed on Thursday that the debts will be paid in 
three years and six months on an installment payment basis after 
two years' grace. 
  The outstanding debts Iran owed to major Korean firms 
totaled 
360 million dollars as of the end of last year. 
  Toward the end of last year, the two sides agreed on the 
payment of the debts in two years after a year's grace period. 
  When the 70 million dollars maturing this year are included, 
the total outstanding debts would total 430 million dollars, the 
source said. 
  This amount represents the debts Iran owes to those 16 major 
industries which maintain branch offices in Iran. When those 
owed to small Korean industries are counted, the total 
outstanding debts would easily run to more than 500 million 
dollars, he said. 

</TEXT>

