<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Camdessus Urges Tokyo, U.S. To Improve Ties </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Camdessus Urges Tokyo, U.S. To Improve Ties </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2504122394 Tokyo NHK General Television Network in 
Japanese 003000 GMT 22 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW2504122394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NHK General Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Announcer-read report over video on an interview with </F>
Camdessus, managing director of the International Monetary Fund, 
with unidentified NHK correspondent on 21 April; place not 
given; from the "NHK News" program -- recorded] 
  [Text] In an NHK interview on 21 April Camdessus, managing 
Director of the International Monetary Fund, strongly urged 
Japan and the United States to improve their relations, saying 
that economic friction between Japan and the United States has 
negative impact on the world economy. 
  [Begin recording] [Camdessus in English, with Japanese 
subtitles] The world has nothing to gain from the dispute. We 
know that the two countries are responsible countries, and they 
will do everything they can to solve this dispute. [end 
recording] 
  Camdessus also stressed that the important thing is for 
Japan 
and the United States to meet halfway. 
  Moreover, he said the United States needs to exert efforts 
to 
reduce its trade deficit, and Japan needs to expand domestic 
demand and open its markets. 
  While asking Japan to continue to introduce economic 
stimulus 
measures, Camdessus said further appreciation of the yen's value 
will hinder economic recovery in Japan. He pointed out the 
importance of cooperation among the developed countries for 
stability of the foreign exchange market. 
  A meeting of finance ministers and central bankers from the 
Group of Seven [G-7] major industrial nations will be held in 
Washington on 24 April. It can be said Camdessus, who will act 
as referee at the meeting, made the recent remark while feeling 
a strong sense of anxiety that Japan-U.S. economic frictions may 
weaken the G-7 member nations' conciliatory stand in the fields 
of foreign exchange policies and economic measures. 

</TEXT>

