<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Would `Welcome' Trade Talks Resumption </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    U.S. Would `Welcome' Trade Talks Resumption </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2204150494 Tokyo KYODO in English 1448 GMT 22 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2204150494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Washington, April 22 KYODO -- The United States 
will welcome the opportunity to resume stalled framework trade 
talks with Japan following the installation of a new government 
in Tokyo, a top White House official said Friday [22 April]. 
  "We would very much welcome the opportunity to continue 
discussion at an appropriate time," Robert Rubin, director of 
the White House National Economic Council, said. 
  Rubin made the remarks following reports from Tokyo that 
Japan's ruling coalition parties have decided to back Tsutomu 
Hata, currently the foreign minister, as their candidate to 
replace outgoing Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa. 
  A vote by Japan's parliament is scheduled for Monday. 
  Rubin told reporters he is aware that Hata has been chosen 
as 
the prime ministerial candidate, but declined to comment whether 
Hata's elevation to the prime ministership would bring changes 
to the troubled U.S.-Japan economic relations. 
  "We have enormous respect for Japan... Our relations with 
Japan are extremely important to us in all respects, including 
economics," Rubin said. 
  In an address he made earlier in the day to a group of 
American business executives, Rubin reiterated that the U.S. is 
not seeking "quotas" or "market shares" for U.S. products in 
Japan. 
  "We are dedicated to try to gain fair access to sell in 
Japan," he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

