Daily Report 
<DATE1>  25 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Crude Oil Imports Said Up 4.2 Percent in Mar </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Crude Oil Imports Said Up 4.2 Percent in Mar </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2504080294 Tokyo KYODO in English 0716 GMT 25 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2504080294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 25 KYODO -- Imports of crude oil in 
March rose 4.2 percent from the year before to 149.26 million 
barrels, posting the second straight month of year-to-year 
gains, the Ministry of International Trade and Industry (MITI) 
said Monday [25 April]. 
  As a result, crude oil imports for fiscal 1993 totaled 
1,613.07 million barrels, up 0.3 percent from the preceding year 
and a gain for the seventh consecutive year. 
  The United Arab Emirates was the biggest supplier of crude 
in 
the reporting month with 39.63 million barrels, followed by 
Saudi Arabia with 27.05 million barrels, Iran with 18.30 million 
barrels and Indonesia with 12.39 million barrels, MITI said. 
  The amount of crude oil processed in March increased 4.0 
percent to 136.24 million barrels, registering the third 
consecutive month of year-to-year gains. Processed crude for 
fiscal 1993 fell 1.7 percent to 1,473.37 million barrels, 
slipping from year-before levels for the sixth year in a row. 
  Fuel oil output for March came to 131.34 million barrels, up 
5.1 percent for the eighth consecutive year-to-year rise. The 
annual total was given as 1,376.31 million barrels, up 3.2 
percent. 
  Fuel oil imports for March rose 6.2 percent to 16.67 million 
barrels while fuel oil exports grew 4.0 percent to 10.13 million 
barrels. 
  Domestic fuel oil sales for March were up the fourth month 
in 
a row, rising 3.1 percent to 142.66 million barrels, a record 
for any month of March. Those for fiscal 1993 edged down 0.4 
percent to 1,428.52 million barrels. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-7430 </DOCNO>
