<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Civilians, Children Hit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Civilians, Children Hit </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU3003141694 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1300 GMT 30 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU3003141694 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Fahrudin Becic from Gorazde] </F>
  [Text] Eight killed and 25 wounded is the tragic result of 
this morning's frenzy of the chetnik artillery men against 
Gorazde. Most of these were civilians, and unfortunately again 
several were children between the ages of three and 10. 
  The (shelling) from the aggressor's strongholds has not 
stopped for long enough to let the guns cool. The area of 
(Gradina) has been pounded with howitzers from the right side of 
Gavran Stijena. They have attempted an infantry attack along the 
Ustipraca-(Mesici) line, and the intensive attacks have not let 
up since last night. 
  It is equally dramatic on the southern part of the front, in 
the region of (Zibovi), (Potrkusa), and (?Oblenceva). At noon, 
the aggressor intensified attacks on the area of Orahovice, on 
the border between the Gorazde and Pale communes. Behind the 
enemy front lines, the new forces of the regular army of the 
so-called Yugoslavia have been grouping. There is no doubt that 
the rest of the day will be even more dramatic. 
  It is hard to believe that high-altitude flights of what are 
probably NATO planes will change anything. When they flew away, 
heavy artillery shells came flying in from the aggressor's 
positions. We do not yet have precise information about the 
consequences. It is particularly hard to obtain information 
from the remote parts of the front. 

</TEXT>

