<F P=100> THE FORMER YUGOSLAV REPUBLIC OF MACEDONIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Envoy To Mediate Conflict With Athens </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    U.S. Envoy To Mediate Conflict With Athens </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2903140494 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1315 GMT 29 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2903140494 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Skopje, 29 Mar (TANJUG) -- Matthew Nimetz, special 
envoy of the U.S. President responsible for the conflict between 
Macedonia [The Former Yugoslav Repulic of Macedonia -- FYROM] 
and Greece, arrived from Athens in Skopje today for talks with 
Macedonian President Kiro Gligorov and Minister of Foreign 
Affairs Stevo Crvenkovski. In a brief press statement following 
an hour and a half of talks, Nimetz was confident that the 
United States would play a useful role in the efforts to resolve 
the conflict between Skopje and Athens. 
  After his visit to Macedonia, Nimetz is expected to return 
to 
Athens. 
  Following his talks with Nimetz, Minister Crvenkovski said 
that the U.S. envoy was told of Macedonia's satisfaction at 
President Clinton's decision to become involved in the conflict 
by appointing an envoy. Crvenkovski said Macedonia was willing 
to resume negotiations to resolve the conflict within the United 
Nations and with Cyrus Vance as mediator. He went on to draw 
attention to Macedonia's view that there were no prospects for 
resuming the dialogue while the pressure of embargo was in place. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

