<F P=100> BULGARIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Matinchev Statement on Economic Situation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Matinchev Statement on Economic Situation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU3003175994 Sofia Khorizont Radio Network in Bulgarian 1600 
GMT 30 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU3003175994 </F>
<F P=104>  Sofia Khorizont Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Bulgarian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Acting Prime Minister Evgeni Matinchev made an 
official statement for the mass media in which he assessed the 
situation in the country. According to him, the government has 
reached the conclusion that the days before signing the 
agreements with the international financial institutes will 
prompt the most acute conflicts from a political point of view. 
  [Begin Matinchev recording] Our opponents know that those 
agreements will be signed in the next few days. On behalf of 
the Bulgarian Government, I want to assure the Bulgarian people 
that precisely those agreements, against the background of the 
strenuous budget adopted by the National Assembly and the 
difficulties that all people experience, will contribute to 
stabilizing the general socioeconomic situation in the country. 
  Unfortunately, precisely at this moment, apparently sensing 
an opportunity to destabilize the country, certain political and 
financial forces are trying to create panic on the foreign 
currency and stock market by disseminating incorrect and 
provocative rumors, thus prompting speculators to purchase 
convertible currency on their behalf in unjustifiably large 
quantities. 
  In the last two days and especially yesterday, this caused 
an 
abnormal and speculative rise in the dollar rate on the foreign 
currency market. [end recording] 
  Further in his statement, Evgeni Matinchev stressed that the 
government is determined to achieve its goals and successfully 
complete the talks with the international financial institutes. 
Together with the National Bank, the government will adopt 
measures aimed at stopping the speculations. 
  Deputy Prime Minister Matinchev appealed to sober 
politicians 
and all citizens to preserve maximum calm, something that would 
guarantee the success of the reforms, prevent the devaluation of 
the Bulgarian lev, and the destabilization of the country. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

