<F P=100> THE FORMER YUGOSLAV REPUBLIC OF MACEDONIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   More U.S. Troops Possible </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    More U.S. Troops Possible </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD3103200294 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1920 GMT 31 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD3103200294 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Skopje, 31 March (TANJUG) -- General John 
Shalikashvili, chairman of the U.S. Joint Chiefs of Staff, said 
at a news conference in Skopje today that U.S. President Bill 
Clinton was ready to send fresh military units to The Former 
Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia [FYROM] as part of the UN 
mission. Shalikashvili said this after talks with Macedonian 
President Kiro Gligorov and Defense Minister Vlado Popovski. 
  Popovski said that they did not discuss the issue of 
establishing an American military base on the Krivolak training 
grounds, adding that the issue "is not on the agenda now." 
  Gen. Shalikashvili today visited American soldiers deployed 
in FYROM. 

</TEXT>

