<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Gorazde `Encircled' by 40 Serb Tanks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Gorazde `Encircled' by 40 Serb Tanks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU3103153594 </F>
<F P=103> AU3103153594 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
BFN 

    [Editorial Report] Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina 
Network in Serbo-Croatian at 1300 GMT on 31 March carries in its 
regular 34-minute newscast several reports updating the fighting 
in the republic. 
  Gorazde correspondent Enes Musovic reports on the continued 
fighting in the region and says that "the fierce fighting, with 
periodic hand-to-hand fighting, has resulted in significant 
losses for the aggressor side. Nevertheless, the (?drugged) 
Chetniks are treading over the dead bodies of their criminal 
colleagues and are themselves being killed. Exceptionally 
fierce and frequent Chetnik infantry attacks are accompanied by 
fierce fire from all types of artillery weapons [words 
indistinct] in the region of (?Zigovi) and [name indistinct] is 
in flames. Everything here is in flames. The Chetniks have 
encircled Gorazde with 40 tanks. Despite heavy losses in 
manpower, the mercenaries of the so-called Srpska republic are 
relentlessly charging on. Some time after 1200 they crossed the 
bridge on the (?Praca) River in Ustipraca with the aim of 
infiltrating the region of Gojcevici and Surovi. They were 
resolutely challenged by Gorazde's defenders. The fighting is 
fierce, but we still have no information on the development of 
these extremely [word indistinct] events." 
  Smajl Terzic reports from Doboj on the situation in the 7th 
South Operative Group's theater of operations and says that "the 
situation in this theater is extremely serious today. The 
aggressor on three occasions attempted to [word indistinct] 
artillery, but [words indistinct]. In the course of the morning 
and the early afternoon, the aggressor has been regrouping his 
manpower and equipment, and has been relentlessly targeting 
civilian targets. Except for material damage, no casualties 
have been reported." 
  An unidentified correspondent from Kladanj reports that 
"[words indistinct] numerous weaponry of all calibers, 62-mm and 
120-m mortars, 105-mm, 122-mm, and 152-mm howitzers, T-55 and 
T-84 tanks (?are being used to shell) both the center and the 
outskirts of the town, and the road communication Kladanj-Tuzla. 
This relentless shelling of the innocent civilian population 
has resulted in the serious wounding of 10 people. No one has 
been killed." 
  Olovo correspondent Amira Salihbasic reports that "the 
aggressor today continued shelling the free Olovo territory with 
long-range artillery. In the morning hours the enemy used PRAGA 
[self-propelled antiaircraft artillery] and mortars to shell our 
defenders' positions in the area of Bacici. The enemy also 
intensified his antiaircraft gunfire. The residential areas of 
the town were also shelled this morning, as were the residential 
areas along the Krivaja River." 
  The studio announcer reads a report from the 1st Corps 
Information Service and says that "the Chetniks today continued 
their usual small arms' provocations from their positions in 
Grbavica, Orlovac, Kromolj, and Sjenicka Kosa. Brekin Potok and 
the area around Vrbanj Most were targeted by various types of 
weaponry, while a rocket from a portable launcher landed on 
Slatina. Enemy snipers were active in several places, so it is 
necessary to exercise caution when moving around the city." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-7504 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu063_i_94006" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-063 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  31 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Muslims Launch Offensive From `Safe Area' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Muslims Launch Offensive From `Safe Area' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD3103184894 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1700 GMT 31 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD3103184894 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Nevenka Marcic] </F>
  [Text] Belgrade, March 31 (TANJUG) -- Bosnian Moslems have 
launched a new offensive, "spring '94", from the Moslem enclave 
of Gorazde, one of the U.N.-protected "Safe Areas" in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina which should have been demilitarized last 
spring, Bosnian Serb military sources said on Thursday. 
  According to the same sources, around 10,000 Moslem fanatics 
are engaged in the five-pronged offensive launched on Tuesday in 
the directions of Cajnice, Rudo and Visegrad, the Bosnian Serb 
towns on the border with the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia, and 
of Grebak and Trnovo, stops on route to Mt. Igman overlooking 
Sarajevo. 
  The offensive's objective is for the Bosnian Moslems to link 
up with the Moslems in the Raska (Sandzak) region in the [word 
indistinct] and have the war spread to Yugoslavia, i.e. its 
republics of Serbia and Montenegro, and to link up the Gorazde 
troops with those on Mt. Igman and in Zepa and Srebrenica, also 
"Safe Areas" in eastern Bosnia-Herzegovina, according to 
information available to the Bosnian Serb army. 
  Bosnian Serb military sources set out that, since Bosnian 
Serb troops are deployed around Gorazde, the town could have 
been supplied with arms and ammunition only by NATO aircraft as 
part of the U.S. operation of air dropping relief aid to 
Bosnian Moslems. 
  The city of Sarajevo and the Moslem enclaves of Srebrenica, 
Zepa, Gorazde, Tuzla, and Bihac were proclaimed U.N.-protected 
"Safe Areas" under U.N. Security Council Resolution 824 in May 
1993. 
  The resolution called for the U.N. peacekeepers to 
demilitarize the "Safe Areas." However, not only have the U.N. 
troops failed to act accordingly but they have even failed to 
take any steps to prevent Moslems from using "Safe Areas" for 
military purposes. 
  U.N. Secretary-General Butrus Butrus-Ghali, himself, said in 
a report to the Security Council in mid-March that Moslems were 
using "Safe Areas" to train, equip and give a rest to their 
troops, and to open fire at Serb positions in the hope of 
provoking Serb retaliation. 
  The U.N. secretary-general urged that the concept of the 
U.N. protected "Safe Areas," in which he said crime and 
prostitution were rampant, be redefined so that "Safe Areas" 
could not be used by Moslems to gain "tactical military 
advantage." 
  However, the U.N. Security Council has failed to take a 
stand on the Butrus-Ghali request, just as it has failed to act 
in the case of similar reports and warnings from the Bosnian 
Serbs. 
  The Bosnian Serb leadership has many times drawn attention 
to 
the fact that Moslem military provocations, in particular from 
Srebrenica and Gorazde, are aimed at forcing Serbs to launch 
military operations against U.N.-protected "Safe Areas" and, 
thereby, securing a foreign military intervention. 
  The warnings from the Bosnian Serbs did not reach the 
Western 
public because Western media have been waging a pro-Moslem i.e. 
anti-Serb propaganda campaign since the outbreak of the war two 
years ago. 
  Therefore, it would not be surprising at all if the latest 
Moslem offensive, launched from the U.N.-protected "Safe Area" 
of Gorazde, was to be disregarded and the Serbs were instead to 
be accused of attacking the town. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

