<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Martic Views Agreement as Recognition of RSK </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Martic Views Agreement as Recognition of RSK </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU3003192694 Belgrade RTB Television Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1730 GMT 30 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU3003192694 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade RTB Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with Milan Martic, leader of the Krajina Serbs, </F>
by Ratko Koprivica on 30 March; place not given -- recorded] 
  [Text] [Martic] We have truly invested the maximum effort 
and honesty in this agreement, and we intend to observe it to 
the maximum. If Croatia does the same....[pauses] However it 
should not use the same things as it has used in the past, such 
as not observing the Erdut Agreement, then I believe that we 
shall soon be able to establish all other relations. 
  The next step would involve the demarcation line; therefore, 
UN Protection Forces [UNPROFOR] troops will be deployed along 
the entire border; in those of our villages where UNPROFOR is 
stationed we will have our police, our authority. Croatian 
villages will be under Croatian authority. The demarcation line 
will have a 1 km width. However, UNPROFOR also has the mandate 
to control 20 km of territory within Croatia, and this is very 
significant. It is very important that, in addition to the 
UNPROFOR forces, we also have the involvement of U.S. and 
Russian diplomacy, which is a guarantee that this agreement will 
be fully observed. 
  [Koprivica] Since you have mentioned diplomacy, what does 
the Zagreb agreement mean for the Krajina in an international 
context? 
  [Martic] It means a lot. The fact that two of the most 
powerful forces -- the United States and Russia -- are 
participating in it, constitutes, in a certain way, the 
recognition of the republic of Serbian Krajina, acceptance of us 
as a reality, a state with its territory, authorities, and 
population. What remains is international recognition, and I 
believe that in the next phase we will be able to achieve this. 
Therefore, it is no longer the case that we are being treated 
only as local authorities -- which has been the case in the past 
-- but as an equal party to a conflict, as in the case of two 
states. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-7517 </DOCNO>
