<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Serb-Russian Friendship Rally Held in Knin </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Serb-Russian Friendship Rally Held in Knin </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD3103190594 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1813 GMT 31 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD3103190594 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Knin, Mar 31 (TANJUG) -- The vice-president of the 
State Duma, lower house of Russian parliamant, and of the 
Liberal-Democratic Party of Russia, Aleksandr Vangerovskiy, 
Thursday said that the Russian people was standing by the 
Republic of Serb Krajina (R.S.K.). 
  Vangerovsky said at a rally of Serb-Russian friendship in 
Knin that Russia was rising from its knees and preparing for a 
campaign to help the R.S.K., adding that great changes were 
underway in Russia which would enable it to send even one 
thousand officers to the R.S.K. if necessary. 
  The rally, at which several thousand Knin inhabitants 
welcomed the State Duma delegation, was also attended by the 
R.S.K. President Milan Martic and Foreign Minister Slobodan 
Jarcevic. 
  Delegation member Yevgeniy Fyodorov, independent Duma 
deputee, expressed gratitude to the R.S.K. on behalf of the 
Russian Army. during the past three years, while Russia was on 
its knees, the R.S.K. was strong enough to successfully protect 
both its own and Russia's freedom. Now the Russian Army is with 
the R.S.K., he said. 
  The R.S.K. was proclaimed in 1991 by the local Serbs in 
their ancestral lands in Croatia, in response to Croatia's 
violent secession from the former Yugoslav Federation and its 
trampling on the local Serbs' rights. 
  The R.S.K. became a U.N.-Protected Area (UNPA) in March, 
1992, but the deployment of the U.N. troops had not deterred 
Croatia from launching four offensives against the territory in 
attempts to impose its rule there by force. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-7519 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu063_k_94010" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-063 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  31 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Thousands Attend Rally </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Thousands Attend Rally </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD3103180794 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1242 GMT 31 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD3103180794 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Knin, 31 March (TANJUG) -- Several thousand people 
gathered at Stojan Jankovic square in Knin today to greet a 
delegation of the Russian State Duma at a meeting of 
Serb-Russian friendship. The meeting was opened by the leader of 
the Serb National Renewal [Srpska Narodna Obnova], Mirko Jovic, 
and was attended by the president of the republic of Serb 
Krajina [RSK], Milan Martic, and the RSK minister of foreign 
affairs, Slobodan Jarcevic. On its visit to Krajina the 
delegation of the Russian parliamentarians is headed by 
Aleksandr Vengerovskiy, the vice chairman of the Duma and of the 
Liberal-Democratic Party of Russia. It also includes Vitaliy 
Sevastyanov, a hero of the USSR, and astronaut Yegeniy Fyodorov, 
an independent Duma deputy. 
  Addressing the people of Knin, Vengerovskiy -- often 
interrupted by tumultuous applause -- said that "Russia is 
rising again and is preparing to come to your help." He said 
that 170 million Russians were behind Krajina and that major 
changes were underway in Russia which would help to bring 1,000 
Russian officers to Krajina if necessary. "We have come here to 
extend our hands and to ensure that we are never separated 
again." It was with enthusiastic applause that Fyodorov's 
following words were greeted: "I express the Russian Army's 
enormous gratitude to you for having found enough strength over 
the last three years, while Russia was on its knees, to defend 
your and our freedom. The Russian Army is now with you." In 
conclusion Fyodorov said: "We are here, you are here, Turks out, 
Americans out." The Russian delegation has had talks with Milan 
Martic, the president of the RSK. 

</TEXT>

